WEBVTT

00:00.701 --> 00:02.336
* Hi, hi, Holly, Holly, hi, hi

00:02.370 --> 00:04.238
* But everyone is minus
you can call me multiply *

00:04.272 --> 00:05.706
* Just --
PAGE: Ian and I have been

00:05.739 --> 00:08.209
traveling around the world,
exploring queer culture.

00:08.242 --> 00:10.278
Woo!
I'm kind of dizzy.

00:10.311 --> 00:12.280
We've witnessed
some incredible things...

00:12.313 --> 00:13.814
Thank you so much.
But have also seen

00:13.847 --> 00:15.583
that many countries still
have a long way

00:15.616 --> 00:18.286
to go in the fight
for LGBTQ rights.

00:18.319 --> 00:20.388
Don't let down your hopes.
And nearly everything

00:20.421 --> 00:22.556
we've experienced
has made us think of home.

00:22.590 --> 00:26.394
So now, we're going cross
country and bringing "Gaycation"

00:26.427 --> 00:27.828
back to America.

00:27.861 --> 00:29.663
* This is me on the regular
so you know *

00:29.697 --> 00:33.434
**

00:35.669 --> 00:42.076
* Did you see them?
Did you see them? *

00:42.110 --> 00:45.079
* They're just walking around,
yeah *

00:47.848 --> 00:51.852
BOTH: "Gaycation: America"
in Saskatchewan!

00:51.885 --> 00:54.255
Ahh!
[ Laughs ]

00:54.288 --> 00:59.360
PAGE: Okay. So, full disclosure:
We're actually in Canada.

00:59.393 --> 01:01.162
But this all used to be one land

01:01.195 --> 01:04.198
before the white man
divided it up.

01:04.232 --> 01:06.367
We are starting our trip
at a First Nations

01:06.400 --> 01:10.371
two-spirit gathering with tribes
from all across North America.

01:12.640 --> 01:14.575
Hi.
Hi.

01:14.608 --> 01:19.280
Could you just explain
what two-spirit means?

01:19.313 --> 01:22.650
We didn't have a word for our,
as you guys call,

01:22.683 --> 01:24.185
gay/lesbian people.
Mm.

01:24.218 --> 01:27.888
And --
and so we coined that word

01:27.921 --> 01:30.824
as an umbrella
for all our tribes.

01:30.858 --> 01:32.826
We never said, "Well,
you're transgender.

01:32.860 --> 01:34.828
You're bisexual.
You're lesbian."

01:34.862 --> 01:36.464
We never knew those terms.

01:36.497 --> 01:38.732
Those are all
from Western culture, you know,

01:38.766 --> 01:40.801
LGBTQ and all that.

01:40.834 --> 01:43.537
So, on some level, it's
about getting rid of labels?

01:43.571 --> 01:46.207
Yes.
Those terms were forced upon us.

01:46.240 --> 01:47.441
Yeah.
You know,

01:47.475 --> 01:49.610
like, a lot of people
think I'm trans.

01:49.643 --> 01:51.179
Mm.
And I said, "No,

01:51.212 --> 01:52.780
I'm not transgender."

01:52.813 --> 01:56.284
I said, "I'm just me.
I'm just Steven."

01:56.317 --> 01:58.552
And I've seen a lot of people

01:58.586 --> 02:00.521
that were non-natives say,
"Oh, I'm two-spirit."

02:00.554 --> 02:02.890
Right.
You know, and I...

02:02.923 --> 02:04.525
Excuse me.
No, you're not.

02:04.558 --> 02:06.694
Yeah.
But I says,

02:06.727 --> 02:09.197
"We've had our lands
taken from you people."

02:09.230 --> 02:10.398
Mm-hmm.
"We've had our culture

02:10.431 --> 02:13.401
taken, our language taken."
Mm-hmm.

02:13.434 --> 02:14.935
"And that was
all stolen from us.

02:14.968 --> 02:17.771
Now, you wanna steal our terms
we picked for our own people?"

02:17.805 --> 02:19.440
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.

02:19.473 --> 02:21.375
I said, "You really need
to go back and look into your --

02:21.409 --> 02:23.777
your own history,
your own culture

02:23.811 --> 02:25.946
and find out your own word
for that"...

02:25.979 --> 02:27.481
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.

02:27.515 --> 02:29.417
"And don't use ours
because it's ours."

02:29.450 --> 02:31.952
Yeah.

02:31.985 --> 02:34.355
WOMAN: I can remember,
when I was younger,

02:34.388 --> 02:35.923
it was never talked about.

02:35.956 --> 02:38.526
You just lived the way
you wanted to live.

02:38.559 --> 02:39.960
And you are who you are...
Mm.

02:39.993 --> 02:43.897
Without anybody
trying to tell you,

02:43.931 --> 02:46.367
like, "Don't live as a woman.
You're a man."

02:46.400 --> 02:48.336
That wasn't talked about.

02:48.369 --> 02:49.870
For me,
it doesn't really matter.

02:49.903 --> 02:51.672
Right.
You can call me what you want.

02:51.705 --> 02:53.641
Just don't call me down.
[ All laugh ]

02:55.709 --> 02:57.211
DANIEL:
What does two-spirit mean,

02:57.245 --> 02:58.812
specifically from you,
what does it mean?

02:58.846 --> 03:01.282
It's having the male spirit,
having the female spirit...

03:01.315 --> 03:02.950
Mm-hmm.
And having both characteristics

03:02.983 --> 03:06.520
and just, um, combined in one
and being one person.

03:06.554 --> 03:07.721
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.

03:07.755 --> 03:09.423
I'm actually
Miss Montana Two Spirit.

03:09.457 --> 03:11.259
My crown and stuff are just
sitting right over there.

03:11.292 --> 03:13.994
You guys can look at them.
It's so beautiful.

03:14.027 --> 03:15.629
PAGE: The term "two-spirit"

03:15.663 --> 03:18.599
was reappropriated in 1990
to represent people

03:18.632 --> 03:21.669
who are queer and indigenous
within the Nations

03:21.702 --> 03:24.805
without displacing
each tribe's unique term.

03:24.838 --> 03:26.974
According to the organizers
of the event,

03:27.007 --> 03:29.310
it is believed
that every tribe and nation

03:29.343 --> 03:33.481
recognized two-spirit people
prior to colonization.

03:35.583 --> 03:37.618
Tonight, we're attending
a powwow.

03:37.651 --> 03:39.520
It's a safe space,
where two-spirit

03:39.553 --> 03:42.356
can express themselves
through dance and celebration.

03:54.001 --> 03:55.636
Yeah.

03:55.669 --> 03:57.471
PAGE: These individuals

03:57.505 --> 04:00.741
were called the gifted ones
and considered healers

04:00.774 --> 04:03.477
that could restore balance
in the universe

04:03.511 --> 04:07.481
with both their male
and female energy,

04:07.515 --> 04:09.683
a far cry from modern labels

04:09.717 --> 04:11.485
and judgments.

04:11.519 --> 04:14.322
[ Vocalizing ]

04:16.790 --> 04:18.692
PAGE:
To me, the two-spirit thing

04:18.726 --> 04:20.961
is just such a clear example

04:20.994 --> 04:24.365
of how being gay
or being trans

04:24.398 --> 04:29.403
is just a natural part
of human existence.

04:29.437 --> 04:32.773
And to have an example of people

04:32.806 --> 04:36.377
who lived
in North America before,

04:36.410 --> 04:39.380
shall I say, we showed up,

04:39.413 --> 04:41.048
existed in a way
that was free.

04:41.081 --> 04:44.652
It's, to me, a clear example
and negates all the people

04:44.685 --> 04:47.821
that say things like,
"This is a Western construct.

04:47.855 --> 04:50.391
This is a modern,
uh, privilege

04:50.424 --> 04:51.792
to even be thinking about,

04:51.825 --> 04:53.394
you know, your sexual identity

04:53.427 --> 04:54.795
or whatever,"
which I've heard before.

04:54.828 --> 04:57.531
And it's like the only
Western construct

04:57.565 --> 05:00.868
is actually homophobia.

05:00.901 --> 05:02.370
That's what --

05:02.403 --> 05:04.004
that's what we brought.

05:06.407 --> 05:08.909
But recently, it seems
like we might be breaking

05:08.942 --> 05:13.681
down the boundaries
we once imposed on ourselves.

05:13.714 --> 05:15.983
A historic day here
at the Supreme Court,

05:16.016 --> 05:18.051
ruling that same-sex marriage

05:18.085 --> 05:22.089
is a nationwide
Constitutional right.

05:22.122 --> 05:27.395
PAGE: On June 26, 2015, history
was made in America.

05:27.428 --> 05:28.829
OBAMA:
This ruling will strengthen

05:28.862 --> 05:30.498
all of our communities

05:30.531 --> 05:33.667
by offering
to all loving same-sex couples

05:33.701 --> 05:36.870
the dignity of marriage
across this great land.

05:36.904 --> 05:39.139
PAGE: In a five-four decision,
the Supreme Court

05:39.172 --> 05:43.977
ruled same-sex marriage legal
under the Constitution.

05:44.011 --> 05:45.879
And 2 days later in New York,

05:45.913 --> 05:48.849
we really have something
to celebrate at Pride.

05:48.882 --> 05:53.454
[ Cheering and applause ]

05:53.487 --> 05:55.489
Oh!

05:59.793 --> 06:01.395
It's a pretty unbelievable time

06:01.429 --> 06:05.466
for LGBT people in America --
and everybody,

06:05.499 --> 06:07.067
for that matter.

06:07.100 --> 06:10.103
And we're celebrating
the joy of being friends.

06:10.137 --> 06:11.639
Yeah.
And queer.

06:11.672 --> 06:14.542
And queer.

06:14.575 --> 06:15.709
Hi.

06:15.743 --> 06:17.044
Hi.
Can we get your --

06:17.077 --> 06:18.679
WOMAN: That's Juno!

06:22.850 --> 06:23.984
Thank you.

06:30.691 --> 06:32.059
DANIEL: Like,
how do you feel about

06:32.092 --> 06:33.060
the Supreme Court decision?
You know, it's every

06:33.093 --> 06:34.762
gay kid's dream, I guess.

06:34.795 --> 06:36.464
I totally want to get married.
She's the...

06:36.497 --> 06:38.198
So I'm -- I'm, like,
the little romantic.

06:38.231 --> 06:41.101
I love it due to the fact
that I can do the same thing

06:41.134 --> 06:42.903
my heterosexual partners can do.

06:42.936 --> 06:45.673
It's a sigh of relief
that we can finally say,

06:45.706 --> 06:47.074
"Okay, this is my husband."

06:48.208 --> 06:50.611
I think being gay
is just validated in,

06:50.644 --> 06:54.682
like, a whole new way
that's pretty major.

06:54.715 --> 06:57.150
While Ian and I can enjoy
living open lives

06:57.184 --> 07:00.053
in big cities like New York
and Los Angeles,

07:00.087 --> 07:01.522
there are still many places

07:01.555 --> 07:03.924
where the atmosphere
for LGBT people

07:03.957 --> 07:05.559
is not the same.

07:05.593 --> 07:07.928
We're visiting a former
Google data scientist

07:07.961 --> 07:09.930
and a New York Times
contributing writer,

07:09.963 --> 07:12.165
who is researching
just how different life

07:12.199 --> 07:15.936
is for queer people
in other parts of the country.

07:15.969 --> 07:17.137
Do you do all
of your research here?

07:17.170 --> 07:18.639
And you just hang out at home?

07:18.672 --> 07:20.240
And I'm, like,
a 99th-percentile introvert.

07:20.273 --> 07:22.009
So...
Yeah.

07:22.042 --> 07:23.711
Uh, this is, like, the extent
of my human interaction

07:23.744 --> 07:25.513
for the last week, so...

07:25.546 --> 07:28.081
So maybe tell us more
about your studies on sexuality.

07:28.115 --> 07:29.583
One of the studies was,

07:29.617 --> 07:31.952
how many men
in the United States are gay?

07:31.985 --> 07:34.622
As the surveys tell us,
only about 1 percent or --

07:34.655 --> 07:36.123
of -- of men are homosexual.
Mm.

07:36.156 --> 07:37.925
And it's clear from the data

07:37.958 --> 07:40.060
that it's more in the range
of about 5 percent.

07:40.093 --> 07:41.829
So what does this suggest?

07:41.862 --> 07:43.797
This suggests a lot of men
in the least tolerant parts

07:43.831 --> 07:45.733
of the country
are in the closet.

07:45.766 --> 07:48.101
So let's look
at pornographic search data.

07:48.135 --> 07:50.538
So is it true
that only about 1 percent

07:50.571 --> 07:52.606
or -- of -- of men
are gay in Mississippi?

07:52.640 --> 07:54.074
Mm-hmm.
But about 4 percent

07:54.107 --> 07:56.910
of pornographic searches
are for gay male porn.

07:56.944 --> 08:00.748
We can also look at what men
search right after gay porn.

08:00.781 --> 08:02.015
Mm-hmm.

08:02.049 --> 08:03.250
And one of the most
common searches,

08:03.283 --> 08:04.652
particularly in
intolerant states,

08:04.685 --> 08:05.986
is "gay test."

08:06.019 --> 08:07.588
You can think
through the mind set of a guy

08:07.621 --> 08:09.590
who searches for gay porn
and then ra--

08:09.623 --> 08:10.991
and then right afterwards a test

08:11.024 --> 08:12.993
probably trying
to convince himself

08:13.026 --> 08:14.862
he's not gay.

08:14.895 --> 08:16.664
Another thing
you see in the data:

08:16.697 --> 08:18.265
What's the most
common completion

08:18.298 --> 08:20.834
for the phrase,
"Is my husband," on Google?

08:20.868 --> 08:23.136
By far, it's,
"Is my husband gay?"

08:23.170 --> 08:24.905
My data would suggest
about 80 percent

08:24.938 --> 08:26.707
of gay men are in the closet,

08:26.740 --> 08:28.208
uh, to some degree and --

08:28.241 --> 08:30.611
and often a large degree, uh,
to the degree they're --

08:30.644 --> 08:32.145
they're marrying women.

08:32.179 --> 08:34.548
I totally Googled things like,
"Am I lesbian?"

08:34.582 --> 08:36.049
and stuff when I was younger,
like trying to...

08:36.083 --> 08:37.250
Oh, yeah. Yeah.
You know, "Am I gay?"

08:37.284 --> 08:39.653
or, "Why don't I like men?" or,

08:39.687 --> 08:41.855
"How do you go down on a girl?"
you know, stuff like that.

08:41.889 --> 08:44.892
Mm-hmm.
It helps.

08:44.925 --> 08:48.195
DANIEL: New York is one
of the most open-minded places

08:48.228 --> 08:49.963
for LGBT people in the country.

08:49.997 --> 08:51.965
Even though there's acceptance
and we have

08:51.999 --> 08:54.234
the U.S. Supreme Court decision,
and it seems like,

08:54.267 --> 08:55.836
you know, America
is at the center

08:55.869 --> 08:59.039
of a progressive situation,
you have a backlash.

08:59.072 --> 09:01.241
And you do have people
that are more aggressively

09:01.274 --> 09:04.244
in the opposite direction.

09:04.277 --> 09:06.614
PAGE: The backlash to
the Supreme Court decision

09:06.647 --> 09:08.649
is most apparent in
the so-called

09:08.682 --> 09:10.183
religious liberty laws.

09:10.217 --> 09:12.853
[ Shouting ]

09:15.288 --> 09:17.758
MAN: We will never
accept homosexual marriage.

09:17.791 --> 09:20.293
I don't care what
Supreme Court justice says what.

09:20.327 --> 09:21.995
PAGE: Among other things,

09:22.029 --> 09:24.632
these laws
allow people and businesses

09:24.665 --> 09:27.768
to discriminate against
same-sex couples on the grounds

09:27.801 --> 09:29.069
that it's against their faith.

09:29.102 --> 09:30.738
WOMAN:
There are at least three states

09:30.771 --> 09:32.172
where judges and clerks

09:32.205 --> 09:34.775
have turned away couples
seeking marriage licenses.

09:34.808 --> 09:37.077
PAGE: Our country was founded
on religious freedom.

09:37.110 --> 09:38.979
But now, that principle
is being bent

09:39.012 --> 09:41.248
to suit an antiequality agenda.

09:41.281 --> 09:43.684
MAN: County clerk Kim Davis
went to jail

09:43.717 --> 09:46.219
for refusing
to give marriage licenses

09:46.253 --> 09:47.821
to same-sex couples.

09:47.855 --> 09:50.023
PAGE: It's a major issue
for many Americans.

09:50.057 --> 09:51.625
So we're off to hear
what the mood

09:51.659 --> 09:53.260
is like in the Heartland.

09:58.131 --> 09:59.733
Hey, Ian.
Hey.

09:59.767 --> 10:02.035
How's it going down there?
We're in Iowa.

10:02.069 --> 10:05.138
PAGE: In the ramp-up to the 2016
presidential election,

10:05.172 --> 10:08.208
Iowa is a battleground
for votes and the first place

10:08.241 --> 10:11.211
to hear the candidates
on the soapbox.

10:11.244 --> 10:13.914
We're here to talk with one
of the country's most prominent

10:13.947 --> 10:16.349
conservative critics
of gay rights,

10:16.383 --> 10:19.019
Texas Senator Ted Cruz.

10:19.052 --> 10:21.855
So we're gonna try and have
some form of interaction

10:21.889 --> 10:25.125
with him, but we'll see.

10:25.158 --> 10:27.360
So sorry.
So how this is...

10:27.394 --> 10:29.062
Thank you.
High school kids...

10:29.096 --> 10:30.798
Hi.
Hi.

10:30.831 --> 10:32.265
DANIEL: Are you Ted Cruz fans?

10:32.299 --> 10:34.167
We're just exploring
the options, yes.

10:34.201 --> 10:36.403
You made a decision?
Uh, no.

10:36.436 --> 10:38.005
Not yet.
No.

10:38.038 --> 10:40.808
PAGE: What is appealing
about Ted Cruz for you guys?

10:42.810 --> 10:45.345
Yeah. In what sense
do you feel you are?

10:52.019 --> 10:53.120
BOTH: Right, right.

10:57.891 --> 11:01.094
[ Cheering and applause ]

11:01.128 --> 11:02.996
WOMAN:
Okay. Watch out, watch out.

11:03.030 --> 11:04.898
Thank you very much.

11:04.932 --> 11:06.767
God bless the great
state of Iowa.

11:06.800 --> 11:09.369
[ Cheering ]

11:09.402 --> 11:10.871
PAGE: Here's a quick primer

11:10.904 --> 11:13.874
on Senator Cruz's position
on queer rights:

11:13.907 --> 11:15.342
He opposes marriage equality...

11:15.375 --> 11:18.912
I have been proud
to defend traditional marriage

11:18.946 --> 11:21.915
as the union of one man
and one woman my entire life.

11:21.949 --> 11:23.917
PAGE: He has urged states
and individuals

11:23.951 --> 11:25.753
to ignore the court's ruling.

11:25.786 --> 11:28.989
He voted against workplace
protections for queer Americans.

11:29.022 --> 11:30.924
He supports those
who deny services

11:30.958 --> 11:32.459
to the LGBTQ community

11:32.492 --> 11:35.028
on the basis
of religious liberty.

11:35.062 --> 11:39.066
And most recently, he campaigned
alongside Kevin Swanson,

11:39.099 --> 11:42.335
a pastor who preaches
on the execution of homosexuals.

11:42.369 --> 11:44.838
Romans chapter one verse 32,
the Apostle Paul

11:44.872 --> 11:46.439
does say

11:46.473 --> 11:49.042
that homosexuals

11:49.076 --> 11:51.278
are worthy of death.

11:51.311 --> 11:53.346
PAGE: And among Republicans,

11:53.380 --> 11:55.816
he's a top choice
for our next president.

11:55.849 --> 11:57.350
Thank you!
And God bless you!

11:57.384 --> 12:01.054
[ Cheers and applause ]

12:01.088 --> 12:03.490
PAGE: I thought he was
gonna answer questions.

12:03.523 --> 12:05.425
Probably shouldn't talk.

12:09.062 --> 12:11.498
PAGE: While we're waiting for
the senator's next appearance,

12:11.531 --> 12:13.901
Ian and I have been invited
aboard the tour bus

12:13.934 --> 12:15.535
of the Bontrager Family Singers.

12:15.568 --> 12:18.238
Hi.
MAN: Hi there. Come on in.

12:18.271 --> 12:20.373
PAGE: They're an Evangelical
Christian musical group

12:20.407 --> 12:23.476
performing at today's rally
for religious freedom.

12:23.510 --> 12:26.479
They tour the country
as an expression of their faith.

12:26.513 --> 12:30.884
So it'll be interesting
to hear their perspective.

12:30.918 --> 12:32.485
DANIEL: You have many more
family members,

12:32.519 --> 12:33.887
but they're all sleeping?
That's right.

12:33.921 --> 12:35.188
Over here?
Sleeping or resting or s--

12:35.222 --> 12:37.124
some of the sort, yes.
We have 10 children.

12:37.157 --> 12:38.959
We're farm folks.
We have a farm...

12:38.992 --> 12:40.493
Yeah.
And spend about 6 months

12:40.527 --> 12:42.863
of the year on the farm and the
other 6 months on the road,

12:42.896 --> 12:44.331
touring with our music.
Awesome.

12:44.364 --> 12:45.966
Awesome.
So...

12:45.999 --> 12:47.367
Are you homeschooled?
Is that how that works?

12:47.400 --> 12:49.036
Road schooled.
Road schooled.

12:49.069 --> 12:50.871
Well-said.
Bus schooled.

12:50.904 --> 12:52.439
Wherever.
Yeah.

12:52.472 --> 12:54.174
But, I mean, uh, clearly,
we're here because I think

12:54.207 --> 12:55.943
it just seems like people
are really passionate

12:55.976 --> 12:57.377
about religious liberty.

12:57.410 --> 12:58.879
And there are people
that are really passionate

12:58.912 --> 13:00.347
about LGBT issues.

13:00.380 --> 13:02.015
I mean, I'm just kind
of wondering your opinion

13:02.049 --> 13:04.084
about how those two things
exist in our country

13:04.117 --> 13:05.485
and, like, what...
I-is there a battle

13:05.518 --> 13:07.520
between the two?
There is a bit of a battle.

13:07.554 --> 13:09.422
But I think the media
plays a lot of that up.

13:09.456 --> 13:12.559
Okay?
A hundred years ago in our U.S.,

13:12.592 --> 13:14.361
this issue wasn't a big issue.

13:14.394 --> 13:17.230
And as a country,
my feeling is,

13:17.264 --> 13:18.866
is farther we
drift away from God,

13:18.899 --> 13:20.567
the more this has crept in.

