50:39.870 --> 50:41.839
"It's Adam and Eve,
not Adam and Steve."

50:41.872 --> 50:44.209
Mm.
And so I got kicked out.

50:44.242 --> 50:46.711
Everything that I've wanted,
you know, was to stop hurting,

50:46.744 --> 50:48.179
to stop the pain
and feel loved.

50:48.213 --> 50:53.684
It does put
such a strain tolerating

50:53.718 --> 50:56.787
that kind of stuff, you know?

50:56.821 --> 50:58.656
I know. Yeah.
Mm.

50:58.689 --> 51:01.826
Like, thinking
that you have somebody

51:01.859 --> 51:05.696
when you have had nobody...

51:05.730 --> 51:07.165
Being here at the Center,

51:07.198 --> 51:08.866
I get, like,
depressed a little bit.

51:08.899 --> 51:12.237
Everybody comes there.
And a lot of them are on drugs.

51:12.270 --> 51:14.672
Meth is so prevalent here.
And it's, like, really...

51:14.705 --> 51:16.574
It's so easy to get to.

51:16.607 --> 51:18.576
Because there is a lot
of sex work out here.

51:18.609 --> 51:19.877
Yeah.
So they do do it

51:19.910 --> 51:21.612
to, kind of, numb themselves.

51:21.646 --> 51:24.182
Not... Yeah, numb themselves
so they don't f...

51:24.215 --> 51:26.751
Because, like, having
to do sex work...

51:26.784 --> 51:29.254
I've honestly done it.
And it's, like --

51:29.287 --> 51:30.621
it's not something that I wanna,

51:30.655 --> 51:32.323
like, have to do again.
Yeah.

51:32.357 --> 51:33.791
Yeah.
But, and, like, feeling

51:33.824 --> 51:35.460
it and all the emotions
rushing to you

51:35.493 --> 51:36.894
while you're doing it's kind of,

51:36.927 --> 51:39.330
like, such a sad thing
to go through.

51:42.667 --> 51:46.471
Right now, we're headed
to the food line.

51:46.504 --> 51:47.505
And...
Yeah.

51:47.538 --> 51:48.639
Who's this?
This is my --

51:48.673 --> 51:50.508
this is my cousin Tink.

51:50.541 --> 51:52.643
She was one of the first people

51:52.677 --> 51:53.878
that, when I was first in L.A.

51:53.911 --> 51:55.613
and I was on the streets,

51:55.646 --> 51:57.848
she really helped educate me.

51:57.882 --> 51:59.717
When I got out here,
like, a lot of stuff

51:59.750 --> 52:02.520
that I know now
I didn't know then.

52:02.553 --> 52:03.821
You have to roll
with the punches

52:03.854 --> 52:05.523
or you're knocked down.

52:05.556 --> 52:07.525
I've been struggling,
doing bad, like, lately.

52:07.558 --> 52:08.859
I'm on the streets every day.
Like...

52:08.893 --> 52:10.895
Okay. Is this part
of your daily routine?

52:10.928 --> 52:12.530
Yes and no.

52:12.563 --> 52:14.599
Okay, 'cause, like,
the way I support myself,

52:14.632 --> 52:16.301
personally... I don't think
I should stand out here.

52:16.334 --> 52:17.735
Like I said, I'm a runner.

52:17.768 --> 52:20.671
Like, so it's easier
at nighttime to disappear.

52:20.705 --> 52:24.275
Book it.
Usually, this is a area,

52:24.309 --> 52:26.711
this gathering,
to make money.

52:26.744 --> 52:28.179
Mm-hmm.
So then, tonight,

52:28.213 --> 52:29.547
what would you...
What's your plan?

52:29.580 --> 52:31.182
I go to the beach.
You go to the beach?

52:31.216 --> 52:33.384
Yeah. I sleep right next
to the water.

52:33.418 --> 52:35.553
We're -- we're lucky that you
gave us

52:35.586 --> 52:37.355
such access into your life.

52:37.388 --> 52:39.390
No one asks this stuff from me.

52:39.424 --> 52:40.925
No one cares.

52:40.958 --> 52:42.827
That you guys are even
trying to get our --

52:42.860 --> 52:45.763
our point of view...

52:45.796 --> 52:49.400
PAGE: These young people have
had to grow up too fast.

52:49.434 --> 52:50.968
Even with
the cultural sea change

52:51.001 --> 52:53.304
of the Supreme Court decision,

52:53.338 --> 52:56.641
many queer youth in America
are still cast out

52:56.674 --> 52:59.677
and find themselves living
on the margins,

52:59.710 --> 53:01.646
hidden in plain sight.

53:09.287 --> 53:13.224
DANIEL: I do think kids in small
towns still, to this day...

53:13.258 --> 53:15.693
It's hard to meet a friend
and talk about being LGBT.

53:15.726 --> 53:17.462
Your family puts the fear in you

53:17.495 --> 53:18.763
that you shouldn't be
talking about it.

53:18.796 --> 53:20.898
It's really behind closed doors.
Mm-hmm.

53:20.931 --> 53:22.967
It feels like walking
on eggshells.

53:23.000 --> 53:24.535
You know?
Mm-hmm.

53:24.569 --> 53:26.304
Someone's just gonna be like,
"Oh," you know?

53:26.337 --> 53:28.873
Yeah.

53:28.906 --> 53:30.775
PAGE: The good news is,
we are at an exciting time,

53:30.808 --> 53:32.777
where more people
are feeling empowered

53:32.810 --> 53:36.414
to represent their experience
on their own terms.

53:36.447 --> 53:39.750
We're meeting Rocco Kayiatos
and Amos Mac,

53:39.784 --> 53:41.652
founders of "Original Plumbing,"

53:41.686 --> 53:43.654
a magazine dedicated
to trans men

53:43.688 --> 53:46.491
and their stories.

53:46.524 --> 53:48.826
Why is there
not as much attention

53:48.859 --> 53:51.862
or representation
for the trans male community?

53:51.896 --> 53:53.331
I ask that
question constantly.

53:53.364 --> 53:54.499
That's the golden question.
Mm-hmm.

53:54.532 --> 53:56.501
And to me,
it's rooted in misogyny.

53:56.534 --> 53:58.269
I mean, at this moment,
I don't feel upset

53:58.303 --> 54:00.805
that I'm not represented
in mainstream media.

54:00.838 --> 54:02.273
I actually feel really grateful

54:02.307 --> 54:04.709
that trans women,
of color specifically,

54:04.742 --> 54:06.511
are given a platform 'cause

54:06.544 --> 54:09.447
I'm not facing
the same struggles.

54:09.480 --> 54:12.417
I get to assimilate into society
in a way that's, like,

54:12.450 --> 54:14.385
a white straight man, you know?
Mm-hmm.

54:14.419 --> 54:16.554
Uh, that's... Obviously,
that's not how I identify.

54:16.587 --> 54:18.956
But that's how I'm read
and observed.

54:18.989 --> 54:22.460
But I feel like a big fear is,
like, am I a real person?

54:22.493 --> 54:23.861
That's just, like,
a baseline fear

54:23.894 --> 54:26.564
I have on a regular basis.
What if someone finds out?

54:26.597 --> 54:28.699
Which feels archaic
at this point 'cause, like...

54:28.733 --> 54:30.034
I still have that fear too,
like, even though...

54:30.067 --> 54:31.702
Yeah.
Like, of not -- not being out

54:31.736 --> 54:33.704
in one of my jobs and just...
Yeah.

54:33.738 --> 54:35.340
Just feeling like, what will
happen if people do find out?

54:35.373 --> 54:36.607
How will they treat me
differently?

54:36.641 --> 54:38.075
How will they see me?
Mm-hmm.

54:38.108 --> 54:39.344
I know, immediately,
they'll think about my genitals.

54:39.377 --> 54:40.578
Like, that's what...
Always.

54:40.611 --> 54:41.779
Goes through my mind.
But it's just...

54:41.812 --> 54:42.980
Yeah.
A fear of, like, being treated

54:43.013 --> 54:44.849
differently and being seen as...
A freak.

54:44.882 --> 54:46.684
Freak.
Right.

54:46.717 --> 54:48.719
On some level, we all share
that experience of,

54:48.753 --> 54:50.988
like, "I'm gonna act
like something I'm not."

54:51.021 --> 54:53.624
Even, like, growing up
in -- in Indiana,

54:53.658 --> 54:55.092
if I could've acted
like I wanted to,

54:55.125 --> 54:56.461
I would be, like, sashaying.

54:56.494 --> 54:58.095
You know, I probably would.

54:58.128 --> 54:59.864
But instead, I'm like, "I'm
gonna have to walk like this."

54:59.897 --> 55:01.466
Yeah.

55:01.499 --> 55:02.700
"I'm gonna have to talk
like this. My voice

55:02.733 --> 55:04.402
is gonna get a little deeper."
Mm-hmm.

55:04.435 --> 55:06.571
And when people would ask me
if I'm gay, I'd be like,

55:06.604 --> 55:07.838
"What did you just say?"

55:07.872 --> 55:09.407
Like, you run off, you know?

55:09.440 --> 55:10.675
And -- and you just
don't acknowledge it.

55:10.708 --> 55:12.343
And, um,

55:12.377 --> 55:15.746
and I feel like I still
go through that today.

55:15.780 --> 55:18.383
As a result
of navigating the world

55:18.416 --> 55:19.684
as a queer person

55:19.717 --> 55:21.486
who is trying to figure out

55:21.519 --> 55:23.120
how to be safe
at all times

55:23.153 --> 55:25.390
and that your relationship
to others

55:25.423 --> 55:26.857
is conditional upon

55:26.891 --> 55:31.562
how you present yourself really
creates barriers.

55:31.596 --> 55:34.399
But when you are a queer kid
and you know that you're queer

55:34.432 --> 55:36.367
and if you're able
to remove all of that

55:36.401 --> 55:37.968
and you're able
to understand how you are,

55:38.002 --> 55:39.637
like, unique and special

55:39.670 --> 55:41.506
and lovable.
Mm.

55:41.539 --> 55:45.876
And that grants you access to
finding healthy relationships.

55:50.881 --> 55:53.017
PAGE: Amos and Rocco
have created a magazine

55:53.050 --> 55:56.053
for anyone
to express themselves freely.

55:56.086 --> 55:59.657
But these safe spaces
didn't always exist.

55:59.690 --> 56:04.395
We're gonna talk to those
who remember a different time.

56:04.429 --> 56:07.998
There are nearly 3 million
queer retirees in America.

56:08.032 --> 56:10.935
And LGBTQ retirement communities

56:10.968 --> 56:13.170
are cropping up
all over the country.

56:13.203 --> 56:16.541
We're meeting seniors
at one such home here in L.A.

56:16.574 --> 56:19.844
to find out what it's like
to be what some call,

56:19.877 --> 56:23.013
"The first generation
of Americans to come out."

56:23.047 --> 56:24.782
I think, though, for the most
part, people,

56:24.815 --> 56:26.517
if you had told them, "Oh,
we're going to

56:26.551 --> 56:27.918
LGBT retirement community."

56:27.952 --> 56:30.087
They'd be like, "Oh,
right, like of course."

56:30.120 --> 56:31.822
"It never occurred to me
before."

56:31.856 --> 56:33.524
Yeah.
Like, yeah, we all age.

56:33.558 --> 56:34.892
Yeah.

56:34.925 --> 56:37.161
They need a place, yeah.
Should we, uh, go up?

56:37.194 --> 56:39.029
This is so nice, honestly.

56:39.063 --> 56:41.065
Our job is to really
help people stay here

56:41.098 --> 56:43.568
as long as possible 'cause
there's so much trauma

56:43.601 --> 56:45.636
for older adults
if they have to move.

56:45.670 --> 56:47.438
And we certainly don't want
our seniors to have to move,

56:47.472 --> 56:49.574
you know, to assisted living
or a nursing home

56:49.607 --> 56:52.443
and feel like they have
to go back in the closet.

56:52.477 --> 56:54.144
[ Knocking ]

56:54.178 --> 56:56.481
Hi, Ed.
Hey.

56:56.514 --> 56:57.815
Hi.
Hi. Wow.

56:57.848 --> 56:59.149
This is nice.
Decorations.

56:59.183 --> 57:01.051
And I have
more pictures in the bathroom.

57:01.085 --> 57:03.187
This is amazing.
Wow.

57:03.220 --> 57:06.657
This thing.
Oh, that's my gay fish.

57:06.691 --> 57:07.958
I -- I think
what would be amazing

57:07.992 --> 57:09.994
would be to hear
your perspective

57:10.027 --> 57:12.563
of what it was like growing up.

57:12.597 --> 57:14.499
I -- I knew
that I liked same-sex.

57:14.532 --> 57:16.734
But there was no words
for it back then.

57:16.767 --> 57:17.968
And you couldn't express it.

57:18.002 --> 57:19.537
You couldn't talk about it.

57:19.570 --> 57:21.506
So you had to live
a double life.

57:21.539 --> 57:23.240
I mean, you could get arrested
at that time.

57:23.273 --> 57:26.143
You could get arrest--
Yes, just for being

57:26.176 --> 57:28.613
in the wrong place
at the wrong time.

57:28.646 --> 57:30.080
And you could get beaten,

57:30.114 --> 57:33.250
which has happened
to me, unfortunately.

57:33.283 --> 57:35.252
They had what they called
the vice squad.

57:35.285 --> 57:37.254
They were the police.
They dressed --

57:37.287 --> 57:39.657
the tight clothes,
a tight pants showing,

57:39.690 --> 57:40.991
whatever, to en --

57:41.025 --> 57:43.661
to entrap you is what --
it was entrapment.

57:43.694 --> 57:47.598
But slowly but surely,
it started getting better,

57:47.632 --> 57:51.101
and I felt more like
I could be myself out here.

57:51.135 --> 57:55.272
And then I met my partner.

57:55.305 --> 57:57.174
We ended up being together
for 34 years.

57:57.207 --> 57:58.175
Oh, wow.
Wow.

57:58.208 --> 57:59.677
He passed away in 2002.

57:59.710 --> 58:00.911
2002?

58:00.945 --> 58:02.279
Sorry.
Sorry to hear that, yeah.

58:02.312 --> 58:03.981
Yeah.
So is this something you thought

58:04.014 --> 58:05.716
that you would see in
your lifetime, a president...

58:05.750 --> 58:07.284
Never.
Talking about gay rights?

58:07.317 --> 58:08.853
Never thought it'd ever happen.
Mm-hmm.

58:08.886 --> 58:11.255
Wow.
Yeah, it's amazing.

58:11.288 --> 58:13.591
We still have more to do...

58:13.624 --> 58:14.892
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.

58:14.925 --> 58:16.527
But it's going
in the right direction.

58:16.561 --> 58:18.162
Who'd have thought it?

58:21.198 --> 58:25.235
MAN: Our first game of the
evening will be a regular bingo.

58:25.269 --> 58:28.939
Woo!

